          <LEXSenses>
            <LEXSense LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="2022-09-13 13:34:17" LastEditedBy="">
              <DefinitionLong/>
              <DefinitionShort>(derivative of {L:ἀρήν&lt;SDBG:ἀρήν:000000&gt;} ‘lamb,’ {D:4.24}) young of sheep ({L:πρόβατον&lt;SDBG:πρόβατον:000000&gt;}); often used for ritual sacrifice; or a sheep of any age</DefinitionShort>
              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>lamb</Gloss>
                <Gloss>sheep</Gloss>
                <Gloss>ram</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>In the one context in the NT, namely, {S:06601301100028}, in which ἀρνίον refers literally to a sheep, it is used in a phrase referring to the horns of an ἀρνίον. In such a context the reference is undoubtedly to a ‘ram,’ that is to say, the adult male of sheep.</Comments>
            </LEXSense>
